Although Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} gives the geometric identification of Koide as a Descartes condition, to our knowledge the outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F}$ has not previously been computed and compared with hadronic observables. We discuss the relation of the present work to existing Koide--quark literature, in particular Rivero's algebraic ``waterfall''~\cite{Rivero2011}, in Section~\ref{sec:notclaims}.

\section{The outer Soddy curvature of the lepton triple}

We have defined the exact comparison quantity as the outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F} \equiv k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$ in Equation~(\ref{eq:k4_geometric}). Two further remarks before computing $\mathcal{F}$.

\paragraph{The function $\mathcal{F}$ in the Descartes framework.}
$\mathcal{F}$ is not chosen from a catalog of symmetric polynomials. Once the Koide relation is read as a Descartes condition (Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes}), the Descartes-determined quantities of dimension $[\text{mass}]^{1/2}$ are the two Soddy curvatures $k_4^{\pm} = e_1 \pm 2\sqrt{e_2}$. The choice between them is binary (inner versus outer), not a continuous selection. We adopt the outer (smaller-curvature) root $k_4^{-}$. The integer power $n$ in any subsequent comparison is fixed at $n=2$ by dimensional consistency: $\mathcal{F}$ has units of $\text{MeV}^{1/2}$, so only $\mathcal{F}^2$ is dimensionally commensurate with a quark mass. The remaining selection freedom --- the choice of comparison quark and the choice of evaluation scale --- contributes to the look-elsewhere effect~\cite{GrossVitells2010} that we quantify explicitly in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}.

\paragraph{Numerical value.}
At the PDG~2024 central charged-lepton pole masses,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F} \;=\; 9.7526\;\text{MeV}^{1/2}, \qquad \mathcal{F}^2 \;=\; 95.1134\;\text{MeV}.
\label{eq:F_value}
\end{equation}
The propagated uncertainty from PDG lepton inputs is $\sigma_{\mathcal{F}^2} = 0.010$~MeV (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}), dominated by the tau mass uncertainty. The value reported in~(\ref{eq:F_value}) is computed as the exact outer Soddy curvature $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2} = 9.752607~\text{MeV}^{1/2}$. The algebraic surrogate~(\ref{eq:F_alg}), $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2} = 9.752823~\text{MeV}^{1/2}$, agrees with $k_4^{\,-}$ to one part in $10^5$; the corresponding difference in the squared quantity is $0.004$~MeV, smaller than the lepton-side measurement uncertainty and negligible compared to the dominant lattice uncertainty of $\approx 0.69$~MeV. In what follows, $\mathcal{F}$ denotes the exact outer Soddy curvature $k_4^{\,-}$ throughout. As a consistency check, the factorization~(\ref{eq:F2_factorization}) gives $\mathcal{F}^2 = \alpha_K^2 \mu_\star = 0.05051 \times 1883.10 = 95.118$~MeV, reproducing the surrogate to the Koide-residual level.

\section{The observation}
\label{sec:observation}

Evaluate the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale,
\begin{equation}
\mu_\star \;\equiv\; m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau \;=\; 1883.1\;\text{MeV},
\end{equation}
by running the FLAG~2024 $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$ estimate~\cite{FLAG2024} $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.44 \pm 0.68$~MeV via four-loop QCD~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$. We treat the quoted $m_s(2~\text{GeV})$ as an $n_f = 4$ $\msbar$ mass and evolve it to $\mu_\star$ at fixed $n_f = 4$ using four-loop renormalization-group running, since both $2$~GeV and $\mu_\star \approx 1.88$~GeV lie above $m_c$. This gives
\begin{equation}
m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \;=\; 95.07 \pm 0.69\;\text{MeV},
\label{eq:ms_mustar}
\end{equation}
where the uncertainty includes the lattice input, the propagation of $\alpha_s$ uncertainty, and four-loop truncation, with the lattice contribution dominating; we decompose this in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. The two sides of the comparison are in different renormalization schemes: $\mathcal{F}$ is constructed from charged-lepton pole masses, while $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ is the FLAG lattice $\msbar$ average run via four-loop QCD. We make no claim of scheme-equivalence between the two sides; the comparison is reported as a numerical relation between objects defined in different schemes, not as a derived equality. Comparing,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \;=\; +0.042\;\text{MeV},
\label{eq:residual}
\end{equation}
or about $+0.061$ standard deviations of the lattice uncertainty. For context, the PDG~2024 quark-mass review~\cite{PDG2024} quotes $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV}) = 92.93 \pm 0.63$~MeV from the latest $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$ calculations; using this value in place of FLAG shifts the comparison residual by approximately $+0.5$~MeV (residual $\approx +0.9\sigma$), remaining well within $1\sigma$. The numerical match is robust to this choice of low-scale input at the level of the conclusions we draw.

\paragraph{Methodological note on order of operations.}
We disclose the order of operations leading to this observation, because it bears on the look-elsewhere assessment in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. The author was investigating Kocik's geometric reading~\cite{Kocik2012} of the Koide relation and computed the fourth (outer Soddy) curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple as a geometric question, with the original motivation being whether the missing fourth curvature might admit a particle interpretation. The numerical agreement $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ was noticed only after the geometric computation was complete, on comparison with a previously consulted reference value for the strange-quark mass. The function $\mathcal{F}$ was therefore not selected from a class of candidate symmetric polynomials of lepton masses; once one takes the ordinary-Descartes reading, it is determined up to the binary inner/outer choice. The choice of evaluation scale deserves separate scrutiny, which we address empirically in Section~\ref{sec:scale_alternatives}.

\section{Robustness}
\label{sec:robustness}

We report robustness checks across six axes: (i) propagation of input uncertainties and decomposition of the error budget, (ii) continuous scale sensitivity around $\mu_\star$, (iii) discrete alternative scale prescriptions, (iv) a null-model Monte Carlo across four prior shapes pre-registered for the Monte Carlo analysis and drawn from the flavor-model literature, (v) lower-cutoff filter sensitivity, and (vi) three supplementary checks (measurement-noise bootstrap, a comparison family of lepton functions, and an exploratory temporal trajectory), each described briefly here and in full in the companion methods note~\cite{Brilliant2026methods}. Central values, lattice-input propagation, and all Monte Carlo output are reproducible from the version-pinned GitHub repository~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}.

All robustness scans in this section use $\mathcal{F}^2 \equiv (k_4^{\,-})^2$ as the comparison quantity, where $k_4^{\,-}$ is the exact outer Soddy curvature defined in~(\ref{eq:k4_geometric}).

\subsection{Input sensitivity and error budget}

Propagating PDG~2024 lepton uncertainties through the exact curvature~(\ref{eq:k4_geometric}) yields $\sigma_{\mathcal{F}^2}^{\text{lepton}} = 0.010$~MeV, dominated by $\sigma_{m_\tau} = 0.09$~MeV. We decompose the running uncertainty on $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ by varying each input independently:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution (MeV) \\
\midrule
FLAG lattice $m_s(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.44 \pm 0.68$ & $0.692$ \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ & $0.051$ \\
Charm threshold $m_c(m_c) = 1.273 \pm 0.005$~GeV (not used for $2~\text{GeV} \to \mu_\star$ evolution) & $0.000$ \\
Four-loop truncation (4L vs 3L) & $0.039$ \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum & $0.695$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
The lattice input dominates by an order of magnitude over all other sources. Decomposing the total variance: the FLAG $m_s(2~\text{GeV})$ input accounts for approximately $99.1\%$, $\alpha_s$ uncertainty for $0.54\%$, four-loop truncation for $0.31\%$, and the lepton-side propagation for $0.02\%$. The lepton side of~(\ref{eq:residual}) is essentially exact at present precision.

One systematic absent from the above decomposition is the QED scheme conversion on the lepton side. Converting the lepton pole masses to $\msbar$ at leading QED order shifts $\mathcal{F}^2$ by approximately $-0.22$~MeV, moving the comparison residual from $+0.042$~MeV to approximately $-0.18$~MeV. The scheme-insensitive band for the residual is approximately $[-0.18,\, +0.04]$~MeV, entirely within $0.3\sigma$ of the dominant lattice uncertainty.

\subsection{Continuous scale sensitivity}

We compute $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ for $\mu/\mu_\star \in [0.5, 4.0]$ and compare against the constant $\mathcal{F}^2$. The intervals over which $|\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)|$ remains within one and two standard deviations of $\sigma_{m_s}(\mu)$ are
\begin{align}
\text{1$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1845,\,1921]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 2.0\%),\\
\text{2$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1808,\,1996]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 5.0\%).
\end{align}
The 1$\sigma$ window is narrow (about $\pm 2.0\%$), confirming that the relation is picking out a specific scale. Running $m_s^{\msbar}$ from $2$~GeV to $\mu_\star \approx 1883$~MeV shifts the mass by $+1.63$~MeV ($+1.7\%$), approximately $39$ times larger than the comparison residual; the scale prescription is not cosmetic. Figure~\ref{fig:convergence} shows historical PDG and FLAG determinations of $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV})$ for context.

\begin{figure}[H]
